John Edward: Language skills essential for world citizens
Scotland’s independent schools continue to excel in academic excellence, which continued with further outstanding exam results in 2018 and is only underpinned by individual and joint achievements in sports, arts, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students from all over Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to care for their students and their parents at the highest level possible.
Independent schools pursue the goal of preparing their students for further education and higher education, the profession of their choice and their place as world citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we see that modern languages are still popular and sought after in schools as electives.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart.”
This is an impressive reminder that we cannot rely solely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s results show that languages with the highest admission rates are at the top of the rankings of independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who learned foreign languages scored A in the higher exams.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students in Mandarin scored A in the higher exams, while 72 percent of students learning German, 69 percent of students learning French, and 63 percent of students learning Spanish also scored A.
This illustrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now considered electives as well as STEM subjects (natural sciences, engineering, and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
According to a survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014, 17 percent of the reasons employers cited for the problems in filling vacancies were related to a lack of language skills.
As a result, language skills are becoming increasingly essential when it comes to preparing young people for their future profession.
As more and more open jobs require languages, this knowledge is essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the profession chosen, young people who have learned a second language will have a real advantage in the future through such a lifelong ability.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give multilingual people an edge over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage (15 percent).
For this reason, it is important for the children of today that we now invest in language teaching.
Children who speak several languages, especially languages of developing countries, will have better chances of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, different languages are taught at all schools.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other languages will teach, which are considered most important for the UK with a view to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Wherever your child’s interests are, independent schools will always have a range of languages available with appropriately specialized teachers.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills necessary for their success, whatever the future may look like.
At this point in a global economic environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still of fundamental importance for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should actually be regarded as "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer young people in Scotland this choice, diversity and excellence.
I'm fine with the fair.
