North Korea rejects unilateral disarmament without confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions deepened its distrust of the United States and under these circumstances the country would by no means unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Organization’s Annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “essential measures last year out of goodwill,” for example, stopping nuclear and missile testing, demolishing the nuclear test site, and committing to not proliferating nuclear weapons and technologies.
"But we do not see a corresponding response from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there is no confidence in our national security, and under these circumstances we will by no means unilaterally disarm first.”
While Ri relied on North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, where North Korea would be rewarded for successive steps, his statement seemed significant in that it did not reject unilateral denuclearization from the outset, as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri pointed to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit meeting between an incumbent US president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, in which Kim had promised to work towards “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump pledged guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the 1950-1953 Korean War, while the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington opposes demands for a loosening of the strict international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on ‘first denuclearization’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal by coercion, and is even opposed to the ‘declaration of the end of the war’,” Ri said.
“The assumption that sanctions can put us on our knees is a fantasy of people who don’t know anything about us.
The problem, however, is that the continued sanctions deepen our distrust."
Ri did not address plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. head of state had highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean head of state Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea were the other party in the denuclearization issue instead of the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have come to this standstill.”
Nevertheless, the tone of Ris speech differed tremendously from his speech last year when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to target the mainland of the United States with North Korea’s missiles after “evil President” Trump referred to Kim as a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
This year, Trump, who had threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea last year, praised Kim at the United Nations for his courage in disarmament, but said there was still a lot of work to be done and that sanctions would have to remain in place until North Korea’s denuclearization.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timeframe for it: “Whether it takes two years, three years or five months – it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council must reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday, “Enforcement of the Security Council’s sanctions must in any case continue vigorously until we have reached full, final and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously strengthened the sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in order to financially dry out Pyongyang’s nuclear weapons and ballistic missile programs.
