Harvard Students Learn to Sleep Enough in a Course
A new course at Harvard University ensures that all undergraduate students get more sleep this year, a measure against the spreading macho culture of staying awake with caffeine and learning all night long.
One scientist has found that students at the world’s leading university are often unnecessary when it comes to caring for themselves.
The course was conceived by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, and he believes it to be the first such course in the United States.
He was inspired to launch the course after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I only learning about this now, in my last year?’
According to her words, no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
This year’s course for the first time explained to students how the basics of good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic performance and also improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university had opted to introduce the course after finding that students suffered severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a range of interactive tasks.
In a section, students see the image of a room in a dorm room and click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise shoes and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the effects of sleep deprivation on athletic performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, and cancer.
They are then encouraged to think about their daily routine using a map of the campus with interactive symbols.
“We know that it will not change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know this – just as you have the right to know how the choice to smoke affects your health,” added Professor Czeisler.
The pride in “sliding a night shift” is still widespread, he said, adding that modern technologies and the ever-increasing pressure on students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Ensuring enough good sleep should be the “secret weapon” of all students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and weight gain could be avoided as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode so that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having taken one of his courses last year in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and encouraged him to push for a university-wide course.
He hopes that in the next step, all postgraduate students will be encouraged to complete a similar study program before starting their studies at the competitive university.
As recommended by Professor Czeisler, students should set up an alarm clock for the time to sleep and wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light", which emanates from electronic screens and LED lighting, and can disrupt the circadian rhythm, leading to problems falling asleep.
