Nevertheless, experts believe that if Beijing plays its cards well, China could benefit from the long-term effects of the trade war by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that a quick political decision in either Washington or Beijing could create the conditions for economic turmoil in both countries is actually much more dangerous than many observers have realized before,” says Abigail Grace, a research associate who focuses on Asia at the Center for New American Security think tank.
Syria is 'ready' for the return of refugees, says Foreign Minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild the country devastated by the seven-year war.
In an address to the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that conditions in the country are improving.
“Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and safer thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government is rebuilding the areas destroyed by terrorists in order to restore normality.
All conditions are now in place for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they had to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian government welcomes assistance in the reconstruction of the devastated country.
However, he stressed that it would not accept conditional aid from countries that had supported the uprising.
Europe wins Ryder Cup in Paris
Team Europa won the 2018 Ryder Cup and defeated Team USA with an end score of 16.5 to 10.5 in the Le Golf National near Paris.
The United States has now lost six consecutive times on European soil and has not won a Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained the crown after the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn reached the 14.5 points needed to defeat the United States.
The American star Phil Mickelson, who had problems over much of the tournament, sunk his tee on the 16th track (Par 3) in the water and lost to Francesco Molinari.
The Italian golfer Molinari was able to shine in all his laps and became one of 4 players to score a 5-0-0 since the tournament began in its current format in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth was defeated 5:4 by the player with the lowest ranking in Team Europe, Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark.
The player with the best ranking in the world, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 to 1 against the Englishman Ian Poulter, who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
The Spanish Sergio Garcia, a veteran from eight Ryder Cups, became the best European Ryder Cup player of all time with 25.5 career points.
“Normally I don’t cry, but today I couldn’t restrain myself.
It was a difficult year.
I am so grateful that Thomas chose me and believed in me.
I'm so infinitely happy to win back the trophy.
It’s about the team and I’m glad to have contributed,” said Garcia after the European victory.
He passes the torch on to his compatriot John Rahm, who won 2-1 in the singles matches against American golf legend Tiger Woods on Sunday.
I’m so incredibly proud to have beaten Tiger Woods, whom I’ve been watching on television since childhood,” said the 23-year-old.
Woods lost all four of his games in France and now has a Ryder Cup record of 13-21-3.
A strange statistic for one of the greatest players of all time, who has won 14 important titles and is only surpassed by Jack Nicklaus.
Team USA had trouble finding the fairways all weekend, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who have performed top-class throughout the tournament.
American captain Jim Furyk said after a disappointing performance of his team: “I’m proud of the guys, they fought.
There was a time this morning when we had put pressure on Europe.
We didn't make anything out of it.
Hats off to Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All 12 of his players performed well.
We will regroup, I will talk to the PGA America and our Ryder Cup committee and we will look forward.
I love these 12 guys and I'm proud to be their captain.
You have to pull the hat.
We were defeated."
Red Tide Update: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota Decline
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier districts, more gaping flowering conditions are recorded, indicating declining concentrations.
A red algae bloom extends over about 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinellas to the south of the Lee district.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places compared to the previous week.
A red tide was also observed in the Pasco district.
In the past week, mean concentrations in or off the coast of Pinellas County were reported, low to high concentrations off the coast of Manatee County, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Charlotte County, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory complaints continue to be reported from Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier districts.
No new respiratory problems have been reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
